node.text:
In March, @AirbnbExperiences hosts all over the world had to stop doing what they love—sharing their interests and passions with others. 
Over the past few weeks, they’ve offered ideas for how to continue hosting even while we’re apart. 
They’ve adapted recipes based on what’s in their pantries, turned living rooms into yoga studios, and choreographed dances for families at home.

Today we’re excited to announce that Airbnb Experiences are now online. You can take a flamenco class with Lidón in Madrid, participate in a tarot card reading with Mak in Austin, or visit a colony of penguins in Cape Town—all from home.

True to Airbnb Experiences in real life, Online Experiences are hosted by remarkable people and set in small groups. Alongside making a new dish, maybe you’ll make a new friend, too.

Thank you to our incredible hosts around the world. We’ll see you online soon —> link in bio.

node.text:
Join Elizabeth for a healing session among the red rocks of Sedona. An artist with Chippewa, Sioux, and English ancestry, she draws from many spiritual traditions—and from the area’s serene landscape. Elizabeth will guide you through a medicine wheel process designed to relieve you of long-carried burdens and provide a new perspective.

Link in bio to get inspired.

node.accessibility_caption: A bedroom with dark blue bedding surrounded by hanging plants from the cieling.

node.text:
Superhost Jessica made her backyard cabin as lively and charming as the walkable Foster-Powell neighborhood that surrounds it. Fuel up first at the Portland Mercado, where the Latin American food carts range from Argentinian to Oaxacan.

Link in bio to avoid FoPo FOMO.

Photo: @sidneyscottmusic
Stay: @fostercabin

node.accessibility_caption:
A detailed image of the red beams with colorful painted arrows and swirled designs against a bright blue sky with the
sun shining in the right corner.

node.text:
A ceiling like this deserves to be stared at by as many people as possible. That’s why Superhost Fabienne designed her Mongolian-inspired yurt with accessibility in mind. She’ll also share all her favorite storybook villages and other day-trip destinations. 

Link in bio for accessible Alsace.

node.accessibility_caption:
A detailed image of the red beams with colorful painted arrows and swirled designs against a bright blue sky with the
sun shining in the right corner.
Inside a yurt with red wood beams, a bed with black comforter and tan canvas walls.

An up close shot of the support beams of the yurt which are a red base color with green, blue, and white swirled
designs.

Inside a converted barn with vaulted ceilings with wooden beams. The charming rustic furniture includes a red couch, yellow armchair, and coffee table to the left of the photo. While towards the right, there is a long kitchen table with a bench on one side and chairs on the other. It is surrounded by cream walls with vertical wood accents.

node.text:
It may be almost half a millennium old, but this barn has been so charmingly converted that guests tend to spend part of their stay planning a return visit. It also doesn’t hurt that Superhosts Michelle and Michael are as generous with their local knowledge as they are with homemade treats. When you’re ready to explore, start by walking into town for a ploughman’s lunch at the Bent Arms. 

Link in bio for East Sussex countryside.

Photo: @thegranarybarn

node.accessibility_caption: A rustic wooden cottage sits surrounded by giant redwood trees.

node.text:
Bask in the serenity of ancient redwoods at Superhost Josephine’s self-described “slightly whimsical sanctuary.” After the morning mist burns off, wander into town to pick up a picnic lunch from the historic Union Hotel, or head out to Bodega Bay, just 20 minutes away. 

Link in bio for gentle giants.

Photo: @suzacruuz

node.accessibility_caption: View from outside a white shepherd's hut looking into it. There is a daybed with white bedding and two pillows with whakes on them. Above the daybed are three shelves full of books and a pengiun trinket.

node.text:
Superhost Mim makes every square inch of her shepherd’s hut call out a warm welcome. Walk five minutes and you’re on the beach, in the countryside, or sitting down at the White Horse for a sandwich of flat field mushrooms and cheese. For a change of pace one night, head to the next village over to catch a show on the water at the Cromer Pier Pavilion Theatre. 

Link in bio for seaside getaway. 

Photo: @thegoodshepherdshut

node.accessibility_caption: Living room with stone fireplace in the right back corner next to large windows looking out to trees. A red patterned rug is in the center with a white couch to the right and two chairs on the left.

node.text:
You don’t have to leave the city to escape it. Follow a path through the woods and over a footbridge to find Superhost Danielle’s handcrafted refuge. At lunchtime, pack a picnic and walk to White Rock Lake or the Dallas Arboretum and Botanical Garden. 

Link in bio for your own little forest in Little Forest Hills.

Photo: @kristen_cook

node.accessibility_caption:
Inside a brick loft with high ceilings where two round light fixtures hang. The room has a table for four, a couch, and a bike hanging on the wall.
The furthest wall is of glass looking outside.

node.text:
The only thing this former factory makes now is happiness. Superhost Gonzalo’s spacious loft puts you in the heart of Colegiales, a quiet neighborhood near the buzz of Palermo Hollywood. To dive into the city’s past and present, walk to the vast flea market nearby.

Link in bio for room to breathe in the city.

Photo: @mybelohost

node.accessibility_caption: Wooden steps lead to a treehouse platform with a round sauna amongst the forest trees.

node.text:
Come home to a tree-sauna after a day on the Golden Skybridge and nearby trails. Sauna access is included with Superhost Jason’s tiny cabin, as is his knowledge of the area, which comes in handy when six different national parks are a short drive away. 

Link in bio for home sweat home.

Photo: @goldentinyhomes

node.accessibility_caption:
French villa with red brick roof, white walls, and a stone hut to the right. A man sits with his feet inside a blue rectangle pool built into a wooden
deck. The deck is surrounded by green grass.

node.text:
Véronique’s renovated farmhouse is perfectly situated for dipping your toes in the Landes countryside—or diving right in. Recent guests have appreciated daily visits from deer, but if you don’t mind missing one, take a day trip to the beaches of the Côte d’Argent. 

Link in bio for villa on historic farm. 

Photo: @philipp_franke26

node.accessibility_caption: An A-Frame cabin with dark green roof and triangle windows look over to uninterrupted views of the southern side of the Zion Mountains in Utah. A bright blue sky with white clouds, the red Zion Mountains, and green trees.

node.text:
The first thing to do after waking up in Superhost Mindy’s tiny A-frame is to open up one side to let in the whole view. Zion National Park is a short drive away, but slot canyon trails even closer will take your breath away just as quickly, by exertion or beauty or both. 

Link in bio for hiking and hot tub. 

Photo: @ethanabitz

node.accessibility_caption: Blue sky above a modern home with a flat roof in the California desert. A man stands in the frame looking at the house.

node.text:
Trent’s hillside roost gives you an elevated view of the desert. For an unforgettable one, scramble up the mountain of boulders right behind the house, ideally in time for sunrise. And don’t wait until your last day to read the guest book, which is packed with local tips.

Link in bio for constellations and coyotes.

Photo: @rockyroostcabin
